@section Synching to CardDAV
Setting up a profile to sync with a CardDAV profile may be a bit confusing at
best, and downright intimidating at worst. Part of the problem is the Store ID
itself is a URL, and it is not a standard - varying from one software to another.

A reminder - CardDAV support is the newest feature in ASynK, and there may be some
rough edges. Also most CardDAV servers do not allow a roll back - like Gmail does - 
to recover any lost data. So convince yourself that ASynK will work for you before
you start using it.

@subsection Creating a profile with CardDAV
@verbatim
   $ ./asynk.py --op=create-profile --name testbbcd --user-dir=~/.asynk.cd --db bb cd --folder default default --store <opath-to-bbdb-file> <CardDAV URL> --cduser=<username>
@end verbatim

Ensure you are able to login to your account properly.
@verbatim
   $ ./asynk.py --op=sync --user-dir=~/.asynk.cd --name testbbcd --dry-run
   $ ./asynk.py --op=sync --user-dir=~/.asynk.cd --name testbbcd
@end verbatim

@subsubsection CardDAV URL to use for the --store parameter
The thing that confuses most people is the CardDAV url which is not in
any standard format. Here are some of the known CardDAV servers, and
the URL that usually works with them. Replace server.org with the name of
your CardDAV server. If your server is not to be found here, a good
way to search the internet for the URL to use is to use a software
like Addressbook in OS X; the same URL will work with ASynK as well.

@enumerate
@item
Apple CalendarServer: https://server.org:8443/ or http://server.org/

@item
OwnCloud: https://server.org/owncloud/remote.php/carddav

@item
Baikal Server: http://server.org/card.php
@end enumerate

Note that for the port number may be optional. If Apple CalendarServer is configured
to respond to both http and https the a port number will be required. Check your 
server documentation.

@subsubsection CardDAV URL to use for the --folder parameter
You can just use ``default'' as the folder ID. But if you feel like using
a specific folder, note that the foid parameter in your state.json should look
like the following for each of the tested CardDAV servers:

@enumerate
@item
Apple CalendarServer: /addressbooks/__uids__/skarrag/addressbook/

@item
OwnCloud: /owncloud/remote.php/carddav/addressbooks/skarra/contacts/

@item
Baikal Server: /card.php/addressbooks/skarra/default/
@end enumerate

@section Synching to Microsoft Exchange
A reminder - Exchange support is the newest feature in ASynK, and there may be some
rough edges. We have taken care to ensure that any deletes from the server
move the contacts to the Trash Bin from where you can recover items if
something goes wrong. However convince yourself that ASynK works fine before
using it with your prodcution data.

@subsection Creating a profile with Exchange
@verbatim
   $ ./asynk.py --op=create-profile --name testbbex --db bb ex --folder default Contacts --store <opath-to-bbdb-file> <Exchange URL>
@end verbatim

The Exchange URL is of the form:
https://outlook.office365.com/EWS/Exchange.asmx - you should ask your system administrator.

Ensure you are able to login to your account properly.
@verbatim
   $ ./asynk.py --op=sync --user-dir=~/.asynk.cd --name testbbcd --dry-run
@end verbatim

If everything works fine, you can try out without the dry-run option.

